\fs28 \cb3 Below is a little nugget about {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/company/uladotapp/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Ula}}. Around 2013, during my time at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/company/flipkart/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Flipkart}}, an e-commerce company in an emerging economy, I realised that general trade or traditional retail is incredibly valuable (70-80% of retail) but highly ignored channel. They're cost effective and hold deep local knowledge. In fact, that might be the only way to service certain products (e.g. Shampoo sachet). However, with improved smartphone access and falling data prices, store owners are more comfortable with tech than ever before. \cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Now, in 2020, the largest component of retail in emerging economies (70-80%) is actively online. But no one has yet gone deep into where they struggle and whether tech can help address those needs. They struggle with inefficient sourcing - not enough selection, buying too much or too little of products at expensive prices. Limited access and expensive working capital exacerbates this problem. \cb1 \
